body:
I also ran into this issue today, using the same gulp recipe.  I was using some transforms (debowerify) and thought that might be the case, but was throwing the same error.

I ended up downgrading back to 7.0.0 to get this working correctly for me for now.

EDIT: Adding my actual task.

``` js
gulp.task('browserify', function() {
     var browserfied = transform(function(filename) {
          return browserify(filename,  {
               debug:      true,
               transform:  ['debowerify'],
          }).bundle();
     });

     return gulp.src(files)
          .pipe(browserfied)
          .pipe(rename({
               extname:    ".dev.js"
          }))
          .pipe(gulp.dest(destination))
     ;
});
```

~~I don't pretend to fully understand everything involved in this, but I believe what's happening in browserify >= 8.0.2 is that by the time you call `bundle()`, browserify has already `end()`ed the pipeline, resulting in `bundle()` no longer returning a writeable stream as vinyl-transform relies on (I think).~~

Ok, I still don't understand the inner workings 100%, but I think I've made progress. I don't believe vinyl-transform relies on the stream returned by `bundle()` being writable in this usage after all. In this case I think the refactored usage of vinyl-transform I suggested works (at least in my test) because the `bundle()` stream is already unpiped by the time the source vinyl-transform piped to it would write, so the write doesn't occur (and doesn't need to).

I think the root cause of the error you guys are running into is the introduction of `process.nextTick(resolved)` to add the transforms. I think that results in the `bundle()` stream being piped to while in the `ended` state (unwritable), with pending write callbacks delaying the `finish` event that would unpipe the stream. So the pipe that vinyl-transform created attempts to write, triggering the error. I think that with the refactored usage I suggested, the write callbacks from the browserify pipeline have time to finish (resulting in it being unpiped before it's written to) because the tick that adds the transforms runs earlier and browserify calls `pipeline.end()` earlier.

I will be interested to see what @substack has to say about this, but I believe there are at least 2 workarounds if you need to use browserify >= 8.0.2 in the meantime:

Where `entry`, `dest`, `b_opts`, and `some_xform` are whatever you want.

Refactor usage of vinyl-transform as described in hughsk/vinyl-transform#1:

``` js
gulp.task('whatever', function () {
  var b, browserified;

  b = browserify(b_opts)
    .transform(some_xform);

  browserified = transform(function (filename) {
    b.add(filename);
    return b.bundle();
  });

  gulp.src(entry)
    .pipe(browserified)
    // ...
    .pipe(gulp.dest(dest));
});
```

Use vinyl-source-stream instead:

``` js
gulp.task('whatever', function () {
  var b = browserify(entry, b_opts)
    .transform(some_xform);

  b.bundle()
    .pipe(vss('bundle.js'))
    // ...
    .pipe(gulp.dest(dest));
});
```

I got around this without vinyl-transform or vinyl-source-stream

``` js
gulp.src('./src/index.js')
    .pipe(through2.obj(function (file, enc, next){
            browserify(file.path)
                .transform('stripify')
                .bundle(function(err, res){
                    // assumes file.contents is a Buffer
                    file.contents = res;
                    next(null, file);
                });
        }))
    .pipe(gulp.dest('./build/'))
```

hope this helps

> that only works if you have 1 entry file per bundle, right?

@jmm you can create a bundle from multiple entries, here is a rudimentary example on how to achieve that 

``` js
gulp.task( 'default', function() {
    var bundler = function() {
        var b = browserify(),
            stream = through2.obj( function( file, enc, next ) {
                // add each file to the bundle
                b.add( file.path );
                next();
            }, function( next ) {
                b.bundle( function( err, src ) {
                    // create a new vinyl file with bundle contents
                    // and push it to the stream
                    stream.push( new vinyl( {
                        path: 'bundle.js', // this path is relative to dest path
                        contents: src
                    } ) );
                    next();
                } );
            } );
        return stream;
    };
    return gulp.src( 'src/js/**/*.js' )
            // multiple entry files going to bundler
            // you can apply jslint, jsbeautify on src files here
            .pipe( bundler() )
            // single bundle file
            // apply minification or/and rename bundle file here
            .pipe( gulp.dest( 'build/js' ) );
} );
```

@jmm -- some clarifications/answers:

To first point about in-file, I don't typically require() files programmatically (`browserify().require()` or `.add()`) in a .js file it looks like a node.js file setup:

``` js
var $ = require('jquery'),
    _ = require('underscore'),
    Backbone = require('Backbone')
;

var example = Backbone.Model.extend({...});

// do more code, etc.
```

for example.  I'm just more used to it this way since I also do a lot of node programming.

As for applying other gulp plugins, it's usually post-browserify-bundling.  

I actually find the through2 way much cleaner than the vinyl-transform way that broke.  I've also found the through2 way to be more forward compatible with versions of browserify that have come out (I did some tests on versions from 7 - 8+).

I needed to browserify multiple files and end up with multipe browserified files, so @aymanrady solution was not right for me, but thanks for letting me in the through2 direction!

My solution ended up looking like this 

```
gulp.task('browserify', function() {
  var bundler = function() {
    var stream = through2.obj(function(file, enc, next) {
      var b = browserify();
      // add each file to the bundle
      b.add(file.path);
      b.transform(reactify)
      b.bundle(function(err, src) {
        if (err) console.log(err);
        // create a new vinyl file with bundle contents
        // and push it to the stream
        stream.push(new vinyl({
          path: file.path.replace('/www/js', ''), // this path is relative to dest path
          contents: src
        }));
        next();
      });
    });
    return stream;
  };
  return gulp
  .src(browserifyFiles)
  .pipe(bundler())
  .pipe(gulp.dest('www/build/'))
});
```

All that work to keep using the gulp.src function!

@aymanrady @clineamb Thanks for the feedback and sorry for the delayed reply. Your participation in the discussion is helpful for understanding what people are doing and why and identifying the pros and cons of various techniques. This thread is a good opportunity to hash out what works and what doesn't, which ideas are keepers and which aren't. The vinyl-transform one (at least the original incarnation @burmisov posted about) is clearly not, as it misapplies vinyl-transform and results in the problem discussed here.

@aymanrady

> you can create a bundle from multiple entries, here is a rudimentary example on how to achieve that

Yes, thanks for the additional example. You can of course adapt it to do more at the expense of more code / greater complexity. By the time you're going to as much trouble as your latest example to get globbing via `gulp.src()`, it's worth considering just bypassing gulp for the globbing, like:

``` js
gulp.task('default', function (cb) {
  var
    glob = require('glob'),
    b = browserify();

  // If desired, can apply transforms to entry file(s) and deps
  b.transform(whatever);

  // If you want multiple entry files => single bundle. Move some logic from
  // `end` to `match` if you want a bundle for each entry file.
  (new glob.Glob('./src/js/**/*.js'))
    .on('match', function (filename) {
      // add each file to the bundle
      b.add(filename);
    })
    .on('end', function () {
      b.bundle()
        // Name bundle whatever you want here
        .pipe(vss('bundle.js'))
        // single bundle file
        // apply minification or/and whatever bundle file here
        .pipe(gulp.dest('build/js').on('finish', cb));
    });
});
```

> multiple entry files going to bundler
> you can apply jslint, jsbeautify on src files here

Is it common that you'd want to apply those things to just your entry file(s) and not the files in the dependency graph?

Here is a variation on yours that does use `gulp.src()`, but eschews manually creating a vinyl object in favor of vinyl-source-stream:

``` js
gulp.task('default', function (cb) {
  var
    through2 = require('through2'),
    b = browserify();

  b.transform(whatever);

  gulp.src('src/js/**/*.js')
    // multiple entry files going to bundler
    // you can apply jslint, jsbeautify on src files here
    .pipe(through2.obj(
      function write (file, enc, next) {
        b.add(file.path);
        next();
      },
      function end (next) {
        b.bundle()
          .pipe(vss('bundle.js'))
          .pipe(gulp.dest('build/js').on('finish', cb));

        next();
      }
    ));
});
```

@clineamb

> To first point about in-file, I don't typically require() files programmatically (browserify().require() or .add()) in a .js file it looks like a node.js file setup:

I think what you're saying is that you typically only have 1 entry file per bundle, right?

> As for applying other gulp plugins, it's usually post-browserify-bundling.

Ok, so it sounds like the pivotal issue for you is being able to do globbing to select 1 entry file per bundle.

> I actually find the through2 way much cleaner than the vinyl-transform way that broke. I've also found the through2 way to be more forward compatible with versions of browserify that have come out (I did some tests on versions from 7 - 8+).

The vinyl-transform way may never have been a good fit, but it certainly isn't now.

Just a reminder that a gulp task is just a stream, and that there are other possible ways to construct the stream than just `gulp.src`. I believe the following is idiomatic:

``` javascript
var browserify = require('browserify');
var gulp = require('gulp');
var source = require('vinyl-source-stream');
var buffer = require('vinyl-buffer');
var uglify = require('gulp-uglify');

gulp.task('default', function () {
    return browserify(['./entry.js']).bundle()
        .pipe(source('app.js'))
        .pipe(buffer())
        .pipe(uglify())
        .pipe(gulp.dest('dist/'));
});
```

If you have multiple input files, passing the output of something like `globby.sync(['./entries/*.js'])` to the browserify function should work in most cases.

**Edit:** See also my comment below for a way to glob without ".sync".

> there are other possible ways to construct the stream

Another possible way of constructing a bundle with multiple entries, that I personally think is easier to understand than using through in the middle of a `gulp.src` constructed stream (though that's not wrong, if you decide you like it).

``` javascript
var through = require('through2');
var globby = require('globby');
var browserify = require('browserify');

gulp.task('default', function() {
  var bundledStream = through();

  bundledStream
    .pipe(source('app.js'))
    .pipe(buffer())
    .pipe(gulp.dest('dist/'));

  globby(['./entries/*.js'], function(err, entries) {
    if (err) {
      bundledStream.emit('error', err);
      return;
    }

    var b = browserify(entries);
    b.bundle().pipe(bundledStream);
  });

  return bundledStream;
});
```

@terinjokes 

> that I personally think is easier to understand than using through in the middle of a `gulp.src` constructed stream (though that's not wrong, if you decide you like it).

I don't know if you're speaking to me or just in general, but putting a through stream in the middle of a `gulp.src()` constructed stream wasn't my suggestion originally. Yesterday I posted a [comment](https://github.com/substack/node-browserify/issues/1044#issuecomment-88980045) with two code examples for using multiple entry files. One was a variation on @aymanrady's suggestion to put a through stream in the middle of `gulp.src()` where I eliminated manually constructing a vinyl object in favor of using vinyl-source-stream. The other was an example of not using `gulp.src()` or a through stream. It's similar to what you just posted except it doesn't use a through stream at all, has a more linear relationship between source code order and event order, and I chose to illustrate calling `b.add()` for each match instead of waiting for all matches and passing them to `browserify()`.
